Hi Zoe! I just wanted to tell you that you not being able to reach your cup is actually more normal than you think. I have some friends and my sister that experience this too but it is fixable! It's as simple as pushing lol. So basically you try to push it down (as if it was a baby haha), which will break the suction and then you'll be able to reach it. One think that I think is HIGHLY important is that cups are usually made out of silicone. The process of producing silicone is EXTREMELY contaminating as it requires high volumes of energy (I'm a chemical engineer btw). I'm telling you this so that you know that it is not helpful either to buy multiple menstrual cups, because they would technically go to waste since you wouldn't use them. Unless you'd be okay with giving those cups to people that would be okay with receiving previously used cups. I understand that there is not cup where 'one size fits all' but maybe try the method I mentioned above before purchasing more cups.
Those tampons sound really great! And if for some reason you can't use a cup, that is a great option to reduce a little bit the single-use plastic that comes out of commercial tampons. But, bear in mind, that in the long run, a cup is definitely better for the environment.
Hope you have a lovely day!
